  <pre>
      <h3><a id="dom">The Dom</a></h3>
      What is the DOM?
      The DOM defines a standard for accessing documents like XML and HTML:
      "The W3C Document Object Model (DOM) is a platform and language-neutral interface that allows programs and scripts
      to dynamically access and update the content, structure, and style of a document."
      The DOM defines the objects and properties of all document elements, and the methods (interface) to access them.
      a good reference is the following site:
      <a href="http://www.w3schools.com/xml/dom_intro.asp"><button type="button">The DOM</button></a>
      The DOM is separated into 3 different parts / levels:
      Core DOM - standard model for any structured document
      XML DOM - standard model for XML documents
      HTML DOM - standard model for HTML documents
  </pre>

  <pre>
    <h3><a id="forms">Forms</a></h3>
      Forms are used to take input from users how visit your website like login or enter credentials and such.
      To make a form you start with the form tags like so: &lt;form&gt; &lt;/form&gt;.
      There are many options for attributes which you can use in a form, here are some examples:
      &lt;form&gt;
        Username: &lt;input type="text" name="username" maxlength=5 size=8 value="Enter name here"/&gt;
      &lt;/form&gt;
      In this example input type 'text' means this box just takes text, as does the 'name'.
      The 'name="username"' here the 'username' stands for the 'id' (name here means id) of the input line, in this case 'username'.
      'maxlength' limits the amount of input of characters, in the example the user can only enter 5 characters.
      'value' here you put the text which goes into the input box to make things extra clear for the user.
      With 'size' you can adjust the length of the input box the user sees on the page.
      To provide the user a chioce we use <span class="line_alink">'radio' buttons</span>, for example when the user has to give his or her gender.
      This can only be male or female (mostly) so you offer a choice like so:
      &lt;form&gt;
        Male: &lt;input type="radio" name="gender" value="male"/&gt;
        Female: &lt;input type="radio" name="gender" value="female"/&gt;
      &lt;/form&gt;
      <form>
        Enter your gender:
        Male: <input type="radio" name="sex" value="male"><br/>
        Female: <input type="radio" name="sex" value="female" />
      </form>

      Now the user has to make a choice and can only pick one because if you click male you cannot click female too.
      When we use the <span class="line_alink">'checkbox'</span> this will work, you can click more options.
      This is set up like so:
      &lt;p&gt;Pick your favorite foods&lt;p&gr;
      &lt;form&gt;
        Fries: &lt;input type="checkbox" name="food" value="fries"/&gt;
        Hamburger: &lt;input type="checkbox" name="food" value="hamburger"/&gt;
        Cheesburger: &lt;input type="checkbox" name="food" value="cheesburger"/&gt;
      &lt;/form&gt;
      The values are for references when using javascript, so we can make this a interactive thing.
      <form>
        Pick your favorite foods:
        Fries: <input type="checkbox" name="food" value="fries"/>
        Hamburger: <input type="checkbox" name="food" value="hamburger"/>
        Cheesburger: <input type="checkbox" name="food" value="cheesburger"/>
      </form>
      When the options are to many you can use the <span class="line_alink">'dropdown' menu</span>.
      It works like this:
      &lt;form&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Where are you from?&lt;p&gt;
        &lt;select name="city"&gt;
            &lt;option value="amsterdam"&gt;Amsterdam&lt;/option&gt;
            &lt;option value="paris"&gt;Paris&lt;/option&gt;
            &lt;option value="berlin"&gt;Berlin&lt;/option&gt;
            &lt;option value="vienna"&gt;Vienna&lt;/option&gt;
            &lt;option value="dublin"&gt;Dublin&lt;/option&gt;
        &lt;/select&gt;
      &lt;/form&gt;
      <form>
        Where are you from?
        <select name="city">
            <option value="option">your town</option>
            <option value="amsterdam">Amsterdam</option>
            <option value="paris">Paris</option>
            <option value="berlin">Berlin</option>
            <option value="vienna">Vienna</option>
            <option value="dublin">Dublin</option>
        </select>
      </form>
      <br>
      <span class="line_alink">'Textarea'</span> is another thing in forms, with textarea you can let
      the user enter text. Like on a dating site where he or she tells more about themselves.
      You do this like so:
      &lt;form&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Tell us about yourself:&lt;p&gt;
        &lt;textarea name="bio" rows="8" cols="40"&gt;
        &lt;/textarea&gt;
      &lt;/form&gt;
      This way you make a textarea, with the 'rows' you can set the hight of the textarea and with
      cols (columns) you set the width.
      <form>
        Tell us about yourself:
        <textarea name="bio" rows="5" cols="30">
  Type here..
        </textarea>
      </form>
